<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 4, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 4, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

After months of delay, Hollywood's television executives
have come up with a plan to protect your children from sex and
violence on the tube.  But don't celebrate yet..  Because, unfortunately,
the only thing it will protect is the big-time producers' ratings.

<p>

In essence, what Hollywood proposes is something like the
current movie rating system.  Each television show would carry
a simple code pegged to the age of the viewer that Hollywood considers
appropriate for each program.  Well!  I'm not impressed.  I just
don't trust Hollywood's opinion of its own product.  Most parents
want to know what a program actually contains.  Does it include
profanity?  Violence or nudity?  Homosexual characters and themes?
Parents want this information before they sit down to watch,
or let their children watch, a program.

<p>

Last spring, President Clinton met with television executives
to encourage them to come up with a system to safeguard families.
After so many months, Hollywood has responded with a dud.  This
is one premiere that deserves a swift cancellation.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwold.html.cgi#current">Last Month's Commentaries</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwdaily.html.cgi#current">This Month's Commentaries</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

<HR SIZE = 3>

<p>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/FRC/images/navstrp2.map">
<img src="/townhall/FRC/images/navstrp2.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
<br>

<font size=-1>
<a href="/townhall/FRC/">FRC Home</a> | 
