<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 13, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 13, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

He has been christened the &quot;butcher of Tienanmen Square,&quot;
and he visited Washington this week, where he was received with
full military honors.  The communist general I am referring to
is China's Minister of Defense --  the same man, the very same
man, who ordered Red Army Troops to crush the unarmed student
protest that captured the world's attention in 1989.  He was invited
to the United States by President Clinton, who came into office
campaigning for human-rights and who has reduced U.S. policy in
Asia to one vast trade mission.

<p>

While the general was getting the red-carpet treatment, the
European Parliament was giving its major human rights award, the
Sakharov prize, to a jailed Chinese dissident, Wei Jing-Sheng.
Mr. Wei's sister received the award on his behalf.  She used
the occasion to remind us that we have betrayed our principles.
We are supporting &quot;a gang of tyrants&quot; in Beijing, she
declared, because we are focused narrowly on &quot;the great Chinese
market of the future.&quot;

<p>

American policy now betrays American ideals.  This was a
week of shame in Washington.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

