<!-----------------Townhall------------------------------>
<I>November 27, 1996</I></center>
<BR>
<BR>

<P><center>
<H2>If They Can't ComplainTax 'Em</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>







	"The town of Colma, Calif., is giving new definition to the old adage that nothing is certain in this world except death and taxes. Town officialsColma is located just south of San Franciscowant to tax every grave that's within city limits at a rate of $5 per year, forever.
<P>
	"The tax would provide a windfall for the city, not only financing Colma's police and fire departments but many other city services as well. . . .
<P>
	"The Colma cemeteries would pay the tax, according to a story in Long Island <I>Newsday</I>, but costs would, of course, be passed on to future customers. Estimates are that the price of burial plots would more than double, to $6,000."
<P>
Stephen Goode, <I>Insight</I>, November 4, 1996
</blockquote>
<!------------------------------------------------------------>
<P>
