<title>November Insider - Events - Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"><br>
<h3>Resource Bank</h3><p>
From the November Edition of <i>The Insider</i><br>

<h2>Events</h2></center>
<hr>

<P>
<b>Heritage Foundation/ALEC State Welfare Reform Conference</b><br>
Washington, DC: December 5, 1996<hr>
<P>
The Heritage Foundation's Resource Bank and the American Legislative Exchange Council (ALEC) will cosponsor a conference on state welfare reform at the Renaissance Washington Hotel in Washington, DC. This day-long conference will assemble hundreds of state legislators, executive branch officials, and think tank and business leaders from across the country to discuss policy ideas for states to manage the devolution of welfare. Confirmed speakers include Wisconsin Welfare Replacement Initiative Project Director Jason Turner, Heritage Senior Policy Analyst Robert Rector, and American Institute for Full Employment Executive Director Theodore Abram. The conference immediately precedes the ALEC National Orientation Conference in the same hotel. CONTACT: Nicole Brungard, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6056, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>, Internet <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>. 
<p><hr>
<p>
<b>ALEC National Orientation Conference</b><br>
Washington, DC: December 3-8, 1996<hr>
<p>
The American Legislative Exchange Council will host its National Orientation Conference for new members of state legislatures in Washington, DC, December 3-8. The conference hopes to offer attendees the information and insights needed for them to launch a successful legislative career.  CONTACT: American Legislative Exchange Council, 910 17th Street, N.W., Fifth Floor, Washington, D.C. 20006, 202/466-3800, fax 202/466-3801.
<p><hr>
<p>
<b>National Taxpayers Conference '97</b><br>
Washington, DC: January 10-12<hr>
<p>
National Taxpayers Union Foundation and Iowans for Tax Relief, in cooperation with The American Spectator, will gather hundreds of tax activists (and would-be activists) seeking lower, fairer taxes at the state and local level. Attendees will learn the nuts and bolts of changing tax and spending policy at home. On Friday, January 10, Steve Forbes and a host of Washington's elected officials will speak. On Saturday and Sunday, there will be training sessions and a luncheon. CONTACT: Cathi Smith, National Taxpayers Union, 703/683-5700, or 1-800-TAX HALT.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Center for Education Policy Foundation</b><br>
Upcoming Events<hr>
<p><ul>
<li>	January 22, 1997: John Fund, Editor, <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>.<br>
<li>	February 12, 1997: "Welfare Reform for the Disabled," by Dr. Kajal Lahiri, Economics Professor and Chair, SUNY Albany.
<li>	March 12, 1997: "The International Monetary System in the 21st Century," by Robert Mundell, Economics Professor, Columbia University.
</ul><p>
CONTACT: Center for Economic and Policy Education, Saint Vincent College, 300 Fraser Purchase Road, Latrobe, PA 15650-2690, 412/537-4597, fax 412/537-4597.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Evergreen Freedom Foundation Legislative Conference</b><br>

Olympia, WA: December 13<hr><p>

EFF is sponsoring a day-long "crash course" in conservative principles and policy for the new Washington State Legislature and staff. Expert speakers from across the country will cover topics including: family policy; tax structure; labor policy; and education reform. Featured guests include: Bob Morrison, Family Research Council; Grover Norquist, Americans for Tax Reform; Richard Vedder, Ohio University; Brenda Reneau, Oklahoma Labor Commissioner; Ray Jackson, Office of Arizona SPI; and Jeannie Allen, Center for Education Reform. CONTACT: Evergreen Freedom Foundation, P.O. Box 522, Olympia, WA 98507, 360/956-3482, fax 360/352-1874.
<p><hr>
<p>
<b>Compassionate Welfare Reform: Empowering Charities and Private Citizens</b><br>
Washington, DC: December 12<hr><p>
The Beacon Hill Institute is sponsoring a forum entitled "Compassionate Welfare Refrom: Empowering Charities and Private Citizens." It will begin at 10:00 a.m. on December 12 in the Caucus Room, Room 345, Cannon House Office Building, Washington, DC. The forum is co-hosted by Sen. John Ashcroft, Sen. Dan Coats, Rep. John Kasich, Rep. Jim Kolbe, Rep. Joe Knollenberg, Sen. Rick Santorum, Rep. James Talent, and Rep. J.C. Watts. The forum will deal with the question of whether government or private charity is better equipped to end dependency. They will also examine what can be done to encourage competition and innovation in the delivery of welfare services. CONTACT: The Beacon Hill Institute, 8 Ashburton Place, Boston, MA 02108-2270, 617/573-8750, fax 617/573-4272, e-mail <a href="mailto:bhi@acad.suffolk.edu">bhi@acad.suffolk.edu</a>.
<p>
