<HEAD>
<TITLE>Publication Reviews -- October Insider -- Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"><P>
<h3>Resource Bank</h3><br>
from the October 1996  Edition of <i>The Insider</i><p>
<a name="table"></a>
<h2>Publication Reviews</h2><p></center>
<b>Table of Contents</b><br>
<a href="#national">National Security & Foreign Policy</a><br>
<a href="#commerce">Commerce, Infrastructure & Regulation</a><br>
<a href="#taxation">Taxation & Budget</a><br>
<a href="#health">Health, Welfare, & Education</a><br>
<a href="#environment">Environment</a><br>
<a href="#crime">Crime & Law</a><br>
<a href="#elections">Elections and Governing</a><br>
<a href="#culture">Culture & Community</a><br>
<P>
<hr>
<a name="national"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>


<P>
<center><b>NATIONAL SECURITY<BR>
&AMP; FOREIGN POLICY</b></center>
<HR>
<P>
<B><a href="http://www.heritage.org/heritage/library/categories/trade/bg1092.html">Restoring American Leadership in Latin America and the Caribbean,</a>
</B><br>
by John Sweeney
<P>
<I>Backgrounder</I> No. 1092, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
Heritage Policy Analyst John Sweeney argues that since Mexico's
economic meltdown in 1994, both the Clinton Administration and
the 104th Congress have allowed America's once-respected leadership
role in Latin America to erode. The Administration and the Congress
have been reluctant to put expansion of NAFTA on the fast track
and instead have allowed the tremendous foreign policy successes
of the Reagan and Bush administrations to fall apart. If this
retreat is allowed to continue, writes Sweeney, U.S. economic
and security interests in the region could suffer a &quot;sustained
decline.&quot; 15 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999,
202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org,</a> Internet
 <a href="http://www.heritage.org">http://www.heritage.org</a>
<P>
<B>Carrying a Small Stick, </B><br>
by Joshua Muravchik 
<P>
<I>On the Issues</I>, American Enterprise Institute<HR>

<P>
Joshua Muravchik, Resident Scholar at the American Enterprise
Institute, argues that the Clinton Administration's foreign policy
is misguided and that this has lead to the erosion of American
military supremacy. According to Muravchik, Clinton's foreign
policy has been a &quot;jumble of improvised responses to crises
and to foreign and domestic political pressures and calculations
of electoral advantage.&quot; The author writes that Clinton nearly
doubled his proposed defense cuts so he could appear to look like
he is reducing the budget deficit, while not having to reduce
domestic spending. A symbol of Clinton's low priority given to
defense is his order for sharp reductions in the development of
strategic defenses. Muravchik also argues that Clinton's policy
with China, North Korea, Serbia, and Somalia, have substantially
hurt America's credibility abroad. Overall, Muravchik concludes,
Clinton's tenure as Commander and Chief has narrowed the wide
margin of security that came about with the demise of America's
Cold War rival. 4 pp. CONTACT: American Enterprise Institute,
1150 17th Street, N.W., Washington, DC  20036, 202/862-5800, fax
202/862-7178. 
<P>
<B>The World Bank's Procurement Myth, <BR>
</B>by John Thibodeau
<P>
<I>Foreign Policy Briefing</I> No. 43, Cato Institute<HR>

<P>
John Thibodeau, Director of Research at Probe International, a
Canadian environmental group, reports that the World Bank's soft-loan
window, the International Development Association (IDA), is losing
many contributions due to its failed projects and the bank's increasingly
risky loan portfolio. The United States recently decided not to
contribute any new money to IDA in 1997, with any future funding
beyond that uncertain. Thibodeau argues that the World Bank has
launched a misleading public relations campaign to convince Congress
and the American public that U.S. taxpayers' contributions to
IDA are beneficial to the American economy. The World bank says
that such contributions are returned in the form of contracts
for U.S. companies. In reality, Thibodeau points out, U.S. firms
receive only about $0.23 in contracts for each $1.00 the United
States contributes to IDA. The IDA gets billions of taxpayer dollars
for bad projects and pork-barrel contracts for a few American
firms. Thibodeau concludes that Congress and lawmakers from other
donor countries should see through the World Bank's desperate
attempt to seek more funds and refuse to waste their constituent's
tax dollars on IDA in 1997 and beyond. 17 pp. CONTACT: Cato Institute,
1000 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200,
fax 202/842-3490, e-mail <a href="mailto:cato@cato.org">cato@cato.org,</a> Internet <a href="http://www.cato.org">http://www.heritage.org</a>
<P><a name="commerce">
<center><b>COMMERCE, INFRASTRUCTURE<BR>
&AMP; REGULATION</b></center><HR>

<P>
<B>The Innovation Age: A New Perspective on the Telecom Revolution,
</B><br>
by Peter Pitsch
<P>
Hudson Institute<HR>

<P>
Peter Pitsch, Adjunct Fellow at the Hudson Institute, and the
former Chief of Staff and Chief of Planning at the Federal Communications
Commission, shows why the United States cannot maintain its preeminent
position in information technology unless it reforms a number
of outdated regulatory restraints. Pitsch shows how artificial
regulations on a market, such as telecommunications, stifles the
progress and productivity that innovations were designed to stimulate.
Pitsch illustrates the superiority of a market-based approach
to regulation, and uses the theories of Austrian school economists
Hayek and Schumpeter to point out the flaws of planned economies.
Overall, Pitsch creates a positive image of what the future can
hold with an open-road policy toward the telecom industry. 120
pp. CONTACT: Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center, P.O. Box 26-919,
Indianapolis, IN  46226, 317/545-1000, 317/545-9639, Internet
<a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson">http://www.hudson.org/hudson</a>
<P>
<B>Lights Out on Federal Power: Privatization for the 21st Century,
</B><br>
by Michael Block and Rep. John Shadegg
<P>
<I>Future Insight</I>, Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation<HR>

<P>
Michael Block, Senior Fellow at the Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation,
and John Shadegg, United States Congressman from Arizona, urge
the privatization of federally owned power facilities. Power Marketing
Administrations (PMAs) were created during the New Deal to provide
a supply of inexpensive power to impoverished rural areas. Block
and Shadegg argue that demographic changes since the 1930s mean
that many of the areas deemed in need of subsidized power are
no longer rural or undeveloped. They argue that PMAs force taxpayers
to provide subsidized power to the rich, and they distort and
hinder competition and productivity in the electric energy market.
Block and Shadegg outline how the federal government should sell
three PMAs. Selling off this large source of frozen assets would
generate nearly $4.5 billion, and help reduce the budget deficit.
Finally, to overcome interest-group oppostion to PMA privatization,
they propose that the current consumers of PMA power be given
the option to purchase shares in the newly privatized PMAs. 7
pp. CONTACT: Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation, 1301 K Street,
N.W., Suite 650 West, Washington, D.C. 20005, 202/289-8928, fax
202/289-6079, e-mail <a href="mailto:mail@pff.org">mail@pff.org</a> Internet <a href="http://www.pff.org">http://www.pff.org</a> 
<P>
<B>Ten Thousand Commandments: A Policymaker's Snapshot of the
Federal Regulatory State,</B> <BR>
by Clyde Wayne Crews
<P>
<I>Regulatory Reform Project</I>, <BR>
Competitive Enterprise Institute<HR>

<P>
Clyde Wayne Crews, CEI Fellow in Regulatory Studies, illustrates
that compliance with federal regulations, which are officially
off-budget, have quietly expanded into costs greater than the
entire GNP of Canada. According to Crews, regulatory costs absorb
almost 20% of the average family's after-tax budget. Politicians
can avoid accountability for more expenses to taxpayers by passing
mandates and regulations that transfer costs to business and consumers
and are not reflected in the budget. Crews warns that a Balance
Budget Amendment may pressure Congress to push even further regulations
that put costs off-budget. He calls for Congress to establish
rules that new agency regulations require Congressional approval,
and to establish a limited regulatory budget. Overall, Crews calls
for making regulatory costs as transparent as direct taxes, and
ensuring that Congress bears direct accountability for every dollar
that agency regulations cost voters. 23 pp. CONTACT: Competitive
Enterprise Institute, 1001 Connecticut Avenue, N.W., Suite 1250,
Washington, DC 20036, 202/331-1010, fax 202/488-0806.
<P>
<B>A Revolution in Regulation: New York Must Treat Employers as
Customers to Compete for the Growth and Jobs We Need</B>
<P>
Public Policy Institute of New York State<HR>

<P>
New York's regulatory bureaucracy is a primary reason that the
state has an image of being hostile to business-and a record of
losing jobs to other locations. In addition to the hassle of overwhelming
amounts of red tape, these regulations can hurt or even shut down
businesses by imposing prohibitive fees, fines and taxes. Employers
must be treated as customers if New York is to compete for the
jobs and growth it needs, according to the Public Policy Institute.
The Institute recommends several steps to achieve regulatory reform,
arguing that key draft regulations should be rewritten before
they become additional burdens to companies. Also, needless regulatory
costs imposed by the Labor Department and the workers' compensation
system should be eliminated. Overall, the report recommends the
laws that limit the powers and responsibilities of regulators
should be enforced, and innovative use of new technologies to
achieve regulatory goals should be allowed to happen. 67 pp. CONTACT:
Public Policy Institute of New York State, 152 Washington Avenue,
Albany, New York 12210, 518/465-7511.
<P>
<B>Regulatory Costs in Profile, </B><br>
by Thomas Hopkins
<P>
<I>Policy Study</I> No. 132, Center for the Study of <BR>
American Business<HR>

<P>
Thomas Hopkins, Adjunct Fellow at the Center for the Study of
American Business, illustrates the vast extent of regulatory costs
in virtually every segment of the U.S. economy. 60 different federal
agencies enact and enforce countless regulations that result in
hidden compliance costs of $668 billion annually. In this book,
Hopkins presents estimates of annual private-sector compliance
costs with federal regulation for 1977 through 2000, and focuses
on the differences in compliance costs among firms. The figures
show that regulatory compliance costs facing all U.S. businesses
rose by $10 billion or more annually in the four years ending
in 1992 after a decade in which such costs generally moved downward.
With the figures presented in this book, Hopkins hopes to bring
a better understanding of the scope and incidence of compliance
costs to help facilitate a more rational debate about the role
and effects of government agency regulations. 25 pp. CONTACT:
Center for the Study of American Business, Washington University,
Campus Box 1208, St. Louis, MO 63130-4899, 314/935-5630, fax 314/935-5688.
<P>
<B>Capital Versus Labor? The Dubious Economics of Class Conflict,
</B><br>
by Alan Reynolds
<P>
<I>Hudson Briefing Paper</I>, No. 195, Hudson Institute<HR>

<P>
Alan Reynolds, Director of Economic Research at Hudson Institute,
responds to the recent mood of hostility toward investors, property
owners, and corporate managers in recent press commentary on the
U.S. economy. Such hostility, according to Reynolds, seems to
be an encouragement toward class warfare between &quot;workers&quot;
and &quot;shareholders.&quot; He argues that the data contradicts
the assertions that workers and shareholders are  natural adversaries.
He points out that workers benefit only when productivity increases,
and that productivity depends on capital investment, which depends
on saving. It is punitive tax policies that explain the recent
sluggish productivity growth that has brought stagnation in employee
wages and compensation. Overall, Reynolds argues, the economy
needs more, not less capital, and the only way to end the stagnation
of employee wages is to decrease punitive tax rates against saving
and investing. 9 pp.  CONTACT: Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center,
P.O. Box 26-919, Indianapolis, IN  46226, 317/545-1000, 317/545-9639,
Internet <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson">http://www.hudson.org/hudson</a>
<a name="taxation"> <P>
<center><b>TAXATION &AMP; BUDGET</b></center><HR>

<P>
<B>An Analysis of the Dole-Kemp Tax Cuts, <BR>
</B>by Gary Robbins and Aldona Robbins
<P>
<I>Issue Brief</I>, Institute for Policy Innovation<HR>

<P>
Gary Robbins and Aldona Robbins, Senior Research Fellows at the
Institute for Policy Innovation, examine the proposed Dole-Kemp
tax cuts. Their analysis finds that the Dole-Kemp plan would boost
the U.S. real growth rate by roughly one-half a percentage point
over the next six years. They scored the proposed tax plan using
both static and dynamic methods. After adjusting for greater incentives
to work, save and invest, the economy, according to Robbins and
Robbins, would be 4.5 percent larger than it would have been without
the tax cuts, and would produce about 2.8 million new jobs. The
growth would offset 35 percent of the $551.3 billion static revenue
loss between 1997 and 2002. A standard distributional analysis
shows that 60 percent of the Dole-Kemp tax cuts would go to taxpayers
earning under $100,000. They also found that although the people
with the lowest 20 percent of incomes pay less than one percent
of federal income taxes, they would receive the greatest percentage
boost of after tax income in higher wages. 16 pp.  CONTACT: The
Institute for Policy Innovation, 250 South Stemmons, Suite 306,
Lewisville, TX 75057, 214/219-0811, fax 214/219-2625, e-mail <a href="mailto:ipi@i-link.net">ipi@i-link.net</a>
Internet <a href="http://www.ipi.org">http://www.ipi.org.</a>
<P>
<B>Understanding Washington State Taxes </B>
<P>
<I>Special Report</I>, Washington Research Council<HR>

<P>
In 1988, the Washington Research Council made a systematic review
of Washington's state taxes, and found the tax system to be fundamentally
sound. Since then, however, there have been a number of changes
in tax rates and bases. This paper, updates WRC's review of the
state tax system using five criteria: economic neutrality, fairness,
administrative simplicity, transparency, and stability. The report
 also provides a history of Washington's state taxes, including
a list of major tax events from 1889 to the present to show how
the state's tax structure has changed over the years. 20 pp. CONTACT:
Washington Research Council, 1301 5th Avenue, Suite 2810, Seattle,
Washington 98101, 206/467-7088, fax 206/467-6957. 
<P>
<B>Public Subsidies, Private Gain: Stop Violating the Oregon Constitution,
</B><br>
by Professor Dale Rubin
<P>
<I>Fiscal Insight</I>, No. 13, Cascade Policy Institute<HR>

<P>
Dale Rubin, Professor of Law at Willamette University, examines
how public subsidies lead to private gain, and how this procedure
violates the Oregon Constitution. He points out that legislators
explain that public expenditures that directly benefit private
individuals, such as professional sports teams, are legal because
they are extended for a &quot;public purpose.&quot; Rubin argues
that this response is simply wrong. He explains that the Public
Purpose Doctrine was not made in order to provide legislators
an excuse to spend taxpayer dollars on whatever project they choose.
In fact, the Oregon Constitution contains clear and unambiguous
clauses that explicitly prohibit the legislature and political
subdivisions from giving any aid to private individuals or corporations.
Rubin argues that the courts' misuse of the Public Purpose Doctrine
has made it possible for public entities to spend public dollars
on almost any private project despite a specific constitutional
prohibition. Rubin argues that the constitutional provisions prohibiting
the commingling of public and private funds have been rendered
meaningless by modern court decisions. 11 pp.  CONTACT: Cascade
Policy Institute, 813 S.W. Alder, Suite 107, Portland, OR  97205,
503/242-0900, fax 503/242-3822, Internet <a href="http://www.CascadePolicy.org">http://www.CascadePolicy.org.</a>

<P>
<B>Should Congress Stop the Bidding War for Sports Franchises?
</B>
<P>
<I>Policy Study</I>, Heartland Institute
<P>
The Heartland Institute has published the testimony from the hearings
on sports franchise relocation held by the Subcommittee on Antitrust,
Business Rights, and Competition of the Senate Committee on the
Judiciary in November 1995. This included four panels by the following:
federal policy makers, sports league commissioners, municipal
authorities, and academics. 4 volumes. CONTACT: The Heartland
Institute, 800 East Northwest Highway, Suite 1080, Palatine, IL
 60067, 708/202-3060, fax 708/202-9799, e-mail <a href="mailto:think@heartland.org">think@heartland.org</a>
Internet <a href="http://www.heartland.org">http://www.heartland.org.</a>
<P>
<a name="health">
<center><b>HEALTH, WELFARE &AMP; EDUCATION</b></center><HR>

<P>
<B>The Prisoners of Charity: Welfare 'Reforms' in New York Have Done Little to Break the Cycle of Dependency</B>
<P>
Public Policy Institute of New York State<HR>

<P>
The Public Policy Institute finds that welfare reforms in New
York have done too little to break the cycle of dependency of
its recipients. After Congress enacted legislation in 1988 intended
to move welfare recipients into the workforce, New York took an
expensive detour to implement legislation that emphasized &quot;back-to-school&quot;
rather than &quot;back-to-work.&quot; These programs were a failure
and caused the percentage of welfare recipients in the job market
to actually drop. The Public Policy Institute argues that in order
for any welfare-to-work strategy to be successful it, must incorporate
programs that make work pay. They also argue that private sector
jobs need to be made to look more attractive compared to welfare
benefits. While raising the minimum wage reduces the number of
entry level jobs, lowering welfare benefits could send more people
into the shelter system-at a greater cost financially and personally.
Instead, the Institute suggests a &quot;fill-in-the-gap&quot;
approach that allows more wages to be kept before welfare benefits
are reduced. They conclude that overall successful reforms will
begin when it is acknowledged that the poor want to, and can,
take responsibility for their future. The report includes a foreword
by United States Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 47 pp. CONTACT:
Public Policy Institute of New York State, 152 Washington Avenue,
Albany, New York 12210, 518/465-7511.
<P>
<B>Arizona's Charter Schools: A Survey of Teachers</B>
<P>
<I>Arizona Issue Analysis</I> No. 141, Goldwater Institute<HR>

<P>
During the Spring of 1996, the Goldwater Institute conducted its
second annual Charter School Survey. The first survey was directed
at parents. The latest survey was aimed at charter school teachers.
Arizona is home to approximately 30 percent of the nation's 350
charter schools. Approximately 16,000 students will attend such
a school during the 1996-97 school year. The results of this survey
tell a great deal about these charter schools, including teachers,
school and classroom configurations, teaching methods, parental
involvement, and students receiving instruction. Additionally,
the survey describes why educators are choosing to teach in charter
schools and offers a glimpse of charter school organization and
school development. 40 pp. CONTACT: Goldwater Institute, Bank
One Center-Concourse, 201 N. Central Avenue, Phoenix, AZ  85004,
602/256-7018, fax 602/256-7045.
<P>
<B>Competition, Choice, and the Structure of Public Education</B>
<P>
<I>Dialogue</I> No. 16, Pioneer Institute<HR>

<P>
This paper is the transcript of a forum sponsored by the Pioneer
Institute on the state and direction of the Boston Public School
System. The forum included these four panelists: James Peyser,
Executive Director of the Pioneer Institute, and member of the
State Board of Education; Neil Sullivan, Executive Director of
the Boston Private Industry Council; Kristen McCormack, charter
school founder and former head of Federated Dorchester Neighborhood
Houses; and Edwin Melendez, Member of the Boston School Committee,
and Director of the Mauricio Gaston Institute at the University
of Massachusetts/Boston. In the opening remarks given by James
Peyser, the failure of school reform is blamed on the underlying
structural defect of public schools-the monopoly power of school
districts. He also argues that spending priorities have been out
of line. While real per-pupil spending has rise by 53 percent
from 1967 to 1991, only 4 percent of it went to regular education-the
core of schools. He argues that public school education priorities
have been driven by politics rather than the needs of the students,
the desires of parents, or the strategies of educators. Peyser
lays out a plan for structural reform of the Boston Public School
System in which there will be a system of schools, rather than
a unitary school system, that will place parents, students and
educators at the center, and will end the political and bureaucratic
constraints that have made past reform efforts fail. 11 pp. CONTACT:
Pioneer Institute For Public Policy Research, 85 Devonshire Street,
8th floor, Boston, MA 2109, 617/723-2277, fax 617/723-1880.
<P>
<B><a href="http://www.heritage.org/heritage/library/categories/education/fyi120.html">How Milwaukee's Choice Program Helps Poor Children Succeed
in School,</a> </B><br>
by Dorothy Hanks
<P>
<I>F.Y.I.</I> No. 120, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
Dorothy Hanks, Research Assistant at The Heritage Foundation,
examines how the Milwaukee School Choice Program, enacted in 1990,
has helped poor children succeed in school. Milwaukee's program
was the nation's first publicly funded school choice program,
and gave low-income parents vouchers to send their children to
private schools. Hanks relays the findings of a recent assessment
of the program by Professors Jay P. Greene of the University of
Houston Center for Public Policy, and Paul E. Petersen of Harvard
University's Program in Education Policy and Governance. Their
study reveals that the reading scores of choice students were
3 to 5 percentile points higher in their third and fourth years,
respectively, than those of comparable low-income public school
students. On math scores, Greene and Petersen found that choice
students were 5 and 12 percentile point higher for the third and
fourth years respectively. Hanks explains, in detail, how the
study was performed, and how it corrected the methodological errors
of previous studies on the subject of school choice. She also
lists a number of other bodies of research that back up the Houston-Harvard
analysis on the value of private schools among urban poor and
minority students. In the conclusion, Hanks emphasizes that the
success of Milwaukee school choice is now a matter of record,
and that it is time for state legislators and members of Congress
to allow low-income children to escape the failing urban public
schools. 5 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation,
214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058,
fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org, </a>Internet <a href="http://www.heritage.org">http://www.heritage.org.</a>
<P><a name="environment">
<center><b>ENVIRONMENT</b></center><HR>

<P>
<B><a href="http://www.heritage.org/heritage/library/categories/enviro/tp16.html">How to Talk About the Environment,</a> <BR>
</B>by John Shanahan
<P>
<I>Heritage Talking Points</I>, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
Despite the presence of serious flaws in current environmental
laws, conservatives have failed to develop a coherent vision of
how these laws ought to be reformed, writes John Shanahan, Environmental
Policy Analyst at the Heritage Foundation. Instead, the debate
about reform usually results in conservatives being falsely characterized
as &quot;anti-environmental.&quot; Shanahan offers an examination
of how conservative critics of our existing environmental policy
can better emphasize the good intentions of present law, and at
the same time, argue for elimination of the sometimes senseless
and oppressive regulations that burden the economy. He shows how
liberal policies have brought little in return for exorbinant
costs, and calls for tapping into the powerful forces and positive
incentives of the market and property ownership-incentives that
reward responsible behavior. Shanahan concludes that Americans
can protect the environment more effectively while simultaneously
increasing economic freedom and growth. 11 pp.  CONTACT: Chris
O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue,
N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org,</a> Internet  <a href="http://www.heritage.org">http://www.heritage.org.</a>
<P>
<B>The Cross and the Rain Forest: A Critique of Radical Green
Spirituality,</B> <br>
by Robert Whelan, Joseph Kirwin, and Paul Haffner
<P>
The Acton Institute<HR>

<P>
Robert Whelan, Assistant Director of the Health and Welfare Unit
of the Institute of Economic Affairs, Joseph Kirwan, a Catholic
Scholar, and Paul Haffner, a lecturer at Pontifical Lateran University,
examine the religious pitfalls of an unqualified embrace of environmentalism.
The authors recognize the necessity of protecting the environment,
but warn that radical environmentalism is essentially hostile
to the Christian tradition in its views of God, human beings and
animals. The authors challenge the radical environmentalist ideology
and present an alternative Christian ecology. 163 pp. CONTACT:
The Acton Institute, 161 Ottawa Street, N.W., Suite 405K, Grand
Rapids, MI 49503, 616/454-3080, fax 616/454-9454, Internet  <a href="http://www.acton.org">http://www.acton.org.</a>

<P>
<a name="crime">
<center><b>CRIME &AMP; LAW</b></center><HR>

<P>
<B>Securities Regulation and the New Law, <BR>
</B>by Mark Gitenstein, Howard Krongard, Steven Toll, and Edward
Yodowitz
<P>
<I>Briefly</I> No. 1, National Legal Center for the Public Interest
<HR>

<P>
This issue of <I>Briefly</I> focuses on the impact of the Private
Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. The act was passed last
year over the veto of President Clinton, and is aimed at ending
the worst abuses of securities class actions. Included are four
panel speeches discussing different aspects of the Act. The first,
by Edward Yodowitz, a Securities Defense Litigator at Skadden
Arps, discusses proportionate liability, pleadings and motions,
and the safe-harbor provision of the new Act. Next, Mark Gitenstein,
a strategist in the Act's passage, warns about a California ballot-initiative
which threatens to reverse the good done by the Act. Howard Krongard,
former General Counsel of Deloitte &amp; Touche, examines the
impact of the Act on the accountant/client relationship. Finally,
Steven Toll gives a plaintiff's perspective. The transcript of
the discussion session following the panelists prepared remarks
is also included. 34 pp. CONTACT: National Legal Center for the
Public Interest, 1000 16th St., NW, Suite 301, Washington, DC
 20036, 202/296-1683.
<P>
<B>Washington Legal Foundation</B>
<P>
Recent Publications<HR>

<P>
 <B>Supreme Court Says Government Must Live Up to Its Contracts,
</B>by Herbert Fenster and Hugo Teufel, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>.
Fenster and Teufel argue that the U.S. Supreme Court's <I>Winstar</I>
decision was a significant victory for all those who contract
with the government. The Court ruled that the government illegally
broke its contract with several savings and loans and ordered
that they be paid damages. 4 pp. 
<P>
<B>Securities Fraud Proposal Threatens California's Economy,
</B>by Theodore Roth, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. Roth argues that
California Proposition 211 will make it easier to file frivolous
shareholder lawsuits and that it attempts to circumvent the 1995
Private Securities Litigation Reform Act. Roth explains the damage
that a baseless shareholder securities fraud suit caused his company
and argues that under this proposition many more small businesses
would be subject to legal harassment and forced settlements. 
pp. 
<P>
 <B>Era of Big Governments Continues With Scrutiny of Menus,
</B>by Elizabeth Toni Guarino, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. Guarino
examines recent actions by the FDA, FTC, and the U.S. District
Court for the District of Columbia which are likely to change
the way restaurants monitor and make claims about the health or
nutrition-related benefits of their fare. It appears that FDA
and FTC, after focusing their powerful regulatory tools on packaged
foods, are now turning attention to the other major segment of
the food industry, restaurants. 4 pp. 
<P>
 <B>The FTC's Global Competition Report: Will It Alter Scrutiny
of Mergers? </B>by Joseph Kattan, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. Kattan
examines a recent Federal Trade Commission staff report on international
competition and discusses what impact it may have on merger review.
As the rate of mergers increases, antitrust regulators have in
turn increased their scrutiny. However, the author points out
that the staff report urges that regulators closely examine the
positive efficiencies the merger creates, and its resulting net
social benefit.  4pp. 
<P>
 <B>Federal Court Chips Away at the Superfund Monolith, </B>by
Seth Jaffe, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. Jaffe analyzes a federal
district court decision that refused to impose liability on  a
company that had contributed to a hazardous waste site. The court
ruled in this manner because the defendant's waste was not the
substance requiring, under the Superfund law, that the site be
cleaned up. Such a rational approach to Superfund, the author
argues, should be affirmed and follow in other cases. pp. 
<P>
CONTACT: Washington Legal Foundation, 2009 Massachusetts Avenue,
N.W., Washington, DC  20036, 202/588-0302, fax 202/588-0386. 
<P>
<a name="elections">
<center><b>ELECTIONS &AMP; GOVERNING</b></center><HR>

<P>
<B>The Political Revolution That Wasn't: Why Term Limits Are Needed
Now More Than Ever, <BR>
</B>by Doug Bandow
<P>
<I>Policy Analysis</I>, No. 259, Cato Institute<HR>

<P>
The issue of term limits will be on fifteen different state ballots
in November. The initiatives are designed to overturn last year's
Supreme Court decision that voided federal term limits. Doug Bandow,
Senior Fellow at the Cato Institute, argues that term limits are
needed, but, that the only way to achieve them is by a constitutional
amendment. Since Congres is unlikely to voluntarily approve one,
Term-limits supporters need to convince 34 states to call for
a convention to draft an appropriate amendment. Bandow believes
that if the states call for a convention that it would encourage
Congress to propose an amendment, in the same way that the Seventeenth
amendment came about.  16 pp. CONTACT: Cato Institute, 1000 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490,
E-mail <a href="mailto:cato@cato.org">cato@cato.org,</a>Internet <a href="http://www.cato.org">http://www.cato.org.</a>
<P>
<a name="culture">
<center><b>CULTURE &AMP; COMMUNITY</b></center><HR>

<P>
<B>Wedlock and Well-Being, </B><br>
by Barry Maley
<P>
<I>Policy Monograph</I>, Centre for Independent Studies<HR>

<P>
Barry Maley, Director of the <I>Taking Children Seriously </I>program
of the Centre for Independent Studies, discusses the importance
of marriage despite the fact that legal, economic and cultural
change makes marriage less necessary and easier to end. In this
paper, Maley looks at ways to give marriage greater legal support
without creating undue obstacles to divorce. He advocates introducing
fault into divorce settlements as a way to indirectly re-enforce
the institution. &quot;Fault&quot; in divorce proceedings is where
one party-for reasons such as violence, substance abuse or child
neglect-is at fault in the marriage and that this should therefore
be taken into account in a divorce settlement. Maley concludes
that this reform would create clear standards of marital conduct
and give incentives for standards to be observed. 32 pp. CONTACT:
The Centre for Independent Studies, P.O. Box 92, Street Leonards,
NSW  2065, Australia, 02-438-4377, fax, 02-439-7310. 
<P>
<B>Family Autonomy and the Charter of Rights: Protecting Parental
Liberty in a Child-Centered Legal System, </B><br>
by Cindy Silver
<P>
<I>Discussion Paper</I> No. 3, Centre for Renewal in Public Policy<HR>

<P>
Cindy Silver, a lawyer in Vancouver, British Columbia, examines
family autonomy and the Canadian Charter of Rights. She observes
that a radical restructuring of the roles and relationships of
the family and state has developed. The state is taking an evermore
active role in protecting child rights as defined under the United
Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child. Silver discusses
the impact on the family of state attempts to both define and
protect &quot;the best interests of the child.&quot; She reviews
certain recent cases that deal with the state superseding parental
rights over a child, and calls for affirming the importance of
the family by, once again, giving explicit recognition within
the Canadian constitution. Finally, she lauds a recent Canadian
Supreme Court decision that renewed recognition of the family
and provided a much-needed balance to the administrative and judicial
polices of the state in cases involving the parent-child relationship.
27 pp.  CONTACT: Centre for Renewal in Public Policy, 46E Sumac
St., Glouster, Ontario K1J 6P7, 613/567-9010, fax 613/567-6061,
e-mail <a href="mailto:crpp@inasec.ca">crpp@inasec.ca.</a>
<p>
