<B><font size=3>The Role of Punitive Damages in Civil Litigation: New Evidence from Lawsuit Filings,  
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Steven Hayward</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Briefing, Pacific Research Institute</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
</FONT>
<P> 
Vice-President of Research at the Pacific Research Institute Steven Hayward looks at the effects of punitive 
damages  in civil litigation, which are demanded in 27 percent of all cases where they are conceivably 
recoverable. Hayward uses lawsuit filing data to show that business and government defendants are four 
times as likely as an individual defendant to face a lawsuit that demands punitive damages. Lawsuits with 
punitive damage demands take one-third longer to resolve than suits without them. Punitive damages tilt 
the playing field towards the demanding parties, according to Hayward, and increase out-of-court 
settlement amounts. Hayward provides evidence against studies that claim the risk of receiving an adverse 
punitive damage judgment is remote. Closer scrutiny of data shows that the probability of punitive damage 
awards is vastly understated by such studies, partly because the data has been improperly qualified and 
mostly because the vast majority of lawsuites are settled out of court where punitive damage demands play 
a significant role. 14 pp. CONTACT: Pacific Research Institute, 755 Sansome St., San Francisco, CA  
94111, 415/989-0833, fax 415/989-2411, e-mail PRIPP@aol.com
<p>

<B><font size=3>Environment and Labor Law  
</FONT></B>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Judicial/Legislative Watch Report, National Legal Center for the Public Interest</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
</FONT>
<P>
The March issue features an article on environmental audits, an analysis of recent Department of Justice 
press releases, and a discussion and key excerpts of the recent decision by the District of Columbia federal 
court of appeals striking down President Clintons executive order banning the use of striker replacements 
by federal contractors. 8 pp. CONTACT: National Legal Center for the Public Interest, 1000 16th St., 
N.W., Suite 301, Washington, D.C. 20036, 202/296-1683, fax 202/293-2118.<p>

<B><font size=3>Washington Legal Foundation 
</FONT></B>
<p>
