<B><font size=3>Citizen Initiatives Under Attack in Colorado, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Paul Grant</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Issue Paper </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
5-96, The Independence Institute </FONT>
<P>
Paul Grant, an attorney in Parker, Colorado, examines the importance of citizen initiatives in that state. He 
reports recent instances of Colorados elected and appointed government officials retaliating against 
initiatives that they are not happy with, and argues that Colorados Secretary of State, General Assembly 
and Supreme Court have combined to weaken the power of initiative. According to Grant, this has been 
done through burdensome new regulations, petty and substantial interference from the Secretary of State, 
legislative attacks on the initiative process, and Colorado Supreme Court interferences. Overall the 
initiative process has been made more difficult, expensive and less effective. Grant looks at the methods 
and motives of attackers of the initiative process, and he considers legal analysis which might be useful in 
resisting and reversing damage caused to this &quot;vital check on runaway government power.&quot; 10 pp. 
CONTACT: Independence Institute, 14142 Denver West Pkwy., No. 101, Golden, CO  80401, 303/279-
6536, fax 303/279-4176.<p>



