<CENTER><font size=5>CRIME &AMP; LAW</font></CENTER>
<P>
<B>The State of Violent Crime in America</B>
<P>
The Council on Crime in America 
<P>
Despite a decline in crime rates in certain American
cities, according to this report the likelihood that Americans
will be victims of violent crime remains at an historic high.
The report illustrates a &quot;revolving door&quot; criminal justice
system in which one in three criminals are under the &quot;supervision&quot;
of the justice system when they commit their criminal act. It
is also shown that violent crime accounted for one-fourth of the
43.6 million criminal victimizations in America in 1993, and that
America potentially faces an explosion of juvenile crime that
will be more violent and random than anything Americans have experienced
to date. Within the next ten years the number of males aged 14-17
will increase by 23 percent, and according to the report, these
juveniles will be more crime prone than their predecessors; commit
more crimes with guns; and commit more crimes against strangers.
58 pp. CONTACT: Lara Stead, The Council on Crime in America Project,
fax 202/822-8328.<BR>

<P>
<B>National Legal Center for the Public Interest</B>
<P>
<B>The
Life of the Law: Principles of Logic and Experience from the United
States,</B> by Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor. The lecture discussed the emerging democracies
from the former Soviet bloc and on the need for an independent
judiciary, free press, and the protection of basic rights. Appendices
include excerpts from <I>The Federalist </I>and Tocqueville's
<I>Democracy in America</I> as well a James Madison's essay on
&quot;Property&quot; and Benjamin Franklin's &quot;An Apology
for Printers.&quot;
<P>
 <B>Congress:
The Year Ahead,</B>
<I>Judicial/Legislative Watch Report.</I> The primary focus of
this issue is on regulatory and tort reform and environmental
law, with a detailed assessment of what legislation is likely
to be taken up this year. The <I>Watch Report</I> also contains
key excerpts from the report by the National Commission on Economic
Growth and Tax Reform, including its recommendation for a flat
tax rate. 8 pp. 
<P>
CONTACT: National Legal Center for the Public Interest, 1000 16th
St., N.W., Suite 301, Washington, D.C. 20036, 202/296-1683, fax
202/293-2118.<BR>

<P>
<B>Crime and Punishment in Texas: Update, <BR>
</B>by Morgan Reynolds
<P>
<I>Policy Report </I>No. 202, National Center <BR>
for Policy Analysis
<P>
According to this study by Morgan Reynolds, National
Center for Policy Analysis Senior Fellow, the reason behind the
sharp drop in the Texas crime rate is due to the increase in prisons
in which more criminals are serving more time. Reynolds points
out that the increased prison capacity in Texas means that criminals
imprisoned for serious crimes can now expect to be in jail for
a longer period of time. Reynolds finds that the overall rate
of crime in Texas has been cut by 30 percent since 1988, and compared
to 1991, the lower crime rate means that 1,140 fewer Texans will
be murdered in 1996 and 450,000 fewer serious crimes against persons
and property will be reported to police. Reynolds argues that
there is a direct link between expected punishment and the crime
rate. According to Reynolds, Texas can reduce crime even further
by continuing to raise expected punishment. 33 pp.  CONTACT: National
Center for Policy Analysis, 12655 N. Central Expy., Suite 720,
Dallas, TX  75243-1739, 214/386-6272, fax 214/386-0924, Internet
<BR>
<a href="http://www.public-policy.org/~ncpa">
http://www.public-policy.org/~ncpa</a>


<P>
<B>Washington Legal Foundation</B>
<P>
Recent Publications
<P>
<B>Biomedical
Product Patent Protection Essential to High Tech Economy, </B>by
Reid Adler and Kate Murashige, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. This
paper provides an analysis of the biomedical product patent protection
process and argues in favor of a broad and supportive patent system
in order to protect industry investment in research and development.
4 pp.
<P>
<B>Endangered
Species Act vs. Private Property Rights, </B>by
Karl Lytz and Kimberly McCormick, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. This
paper analyzes the federal court's interpretation of the Endangered
Species Act's definition of &quot;harm&quot; for the purposes
of an unlawful &quot;take&quot; in the context of habitat modification
and argues that thanks to the law's inflexible provisions, private
property owners' rights have been diminished in favor of species
protection. 4 pp.
<P>
<B>The
Congressional Subpoena Power, </B>by
Douglas Cox, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. This paper examines the
power that each House of Congress has in exercising a congressional
subpoena and analyzes the three possible routes to seek enforcement
of a subpoena, as well as a host of other tools the Congress can
use to obtain information and testimony. 4 pp.
<P>
<B>Courts
Should Intensify Scrutiny of Mass Tort Class Action Lawsuits,
</B>by John Isbister,
<I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. This <I>Backgrounder</I> discusses
the numerous issues posed by nationwide class action lawsuits
and argues that while there are clear benefits to class actions,
the courts must carefully scrutinize the negative effects of class
action certification in mass tort cases. 4 pp.
<P>
<B>Using
Compliance Programs And Internal Investigations to Protect Confidential
Information, </B>by
Jay Stephens and David Haug, <I>Contemporary Legal Note</I>. This
paper outlines the attributes and elements of an effective corporate
compliance program and gives guidance on whether in-house or outside
counsel should be used to conduct the compliance program and internal
audits. The paper also provides practical suggestions on protecting
the confidentiality of information generated by compliance programs.
16 pp.
<P>
CONTACT: Washington Legal Foundation, 2009 Massachusetts Avenue,
N.W. Washington, D.C. 20036, 202/588-0302.<BR>
