reasons or because they believe that public or private schools
do not have strong enough academic standards. Regardless of the
reason. However, Olasky maintains that homeschooling has proven
very successful at educating children</FONT><I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">-</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">to
the consternation of the education establishment. At last year's
NEA convention, members voted in an anti-homeschool resolution
advocating its regulation. Overall, concludes Olasky, homeschoolers
feel the benefits of their method of education outweighs their
sacrifices. 8 pp.  CONTACT: Capital Research Center, 727 15th
