<P>
<B><font size=3>End Compulsory Schooling, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Sheldon Richman and David Kopel</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Independence Issue Paper</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 1-96, Independence Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>David Kopel, Research Director at the Independence
Institute, and Sheldon Richman, Policy Analyst with the Cato Institute,
argue that the issue of compulsory schooling needs serious reconsideration.
Kopel and Richman point out that early proponents of compulsory
education often implied in their advocacy that the home was a
bad influence on children, particularly children of working-class
and immigrant families. Most people, according to Kopel and Richman,
are unaware that the compulsory education system was designed
to save children from the bad influence of their parents. The
paper shows that education in the days before government compulsion
produced high rates of literacy. Kopel and Richman point out problems
with compulsory schooling and how it harms education, as well
as dealing with the issue of irresponsible parents. 16 pp. CONTACT:
Independence Institute, 14142 Denver West Pkwy., No. 101, Golden,
CO  80401, 303/279-6536, fax 303/279-4176.<BR>
