<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>CULTURE &AMP; COMMUNITY</FONT></CENTER>


<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/family/bg1064.html">Why Religion Matters: The Impact of Religious Practice on Social Stability</a>, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Patrick Fagan</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
1064, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Patrick Fagan, William H.G. FitzGerald Fellow at
Heritage, has found that nearly every major study on the impact
of religion demonstrates its positive impact on a host of social
problems. He gives evidence that religious practice strengthens
the family and brings satisfaction to marriage; helps poor people
move out of poverty; aids substantially in the formation of personal
moral judgement; and inoculates individuals against such social
problems as suicide, drug abuse, out-of-wedlock births, crime
and divorce. According to Fagan, Washington policy-makers should
consider the enormous contribution religion can make toward solving
America's major social problems. Fagan offers several steps that
Congress and the President can take to encourage religious practice,
including: the initiation of a national discussion on the need
to restore the role of religion in American life; passage of a
resolution affirming the census data on the extent of religious
practice; and the appointment of judges who are at least more
sensitive to the role of religion in public life. 29 pp.  CONTACT:
Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail Insider@heritage.org.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Bringing out the Worst in Us: The Frightening
Truth about Violence, the Media and Our Youth, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Bob Waliszewski &amp; Jerry Melchisedeck</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Focus on the Family Culture Report</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">,
Focus on the Family</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Focus on the Family has issued this report to challenge
the entertainment industry to accept responsibility for the effects
that media has on the behavior of young people. <I>Bringing Out
the Worst in Us</I> examines the link between Hollywood horrors
bombarding the American public and violent acts that mimic them.
Research presented in the report links the following: guns in
Hollywood and guns on the street; Rap violence and street violence;
rock idol suicide and teen suicide; violent crimes in film and
violent crimes among youth; and serial killer movies and violent
murders.<I> </I>64 pp.  CONTACT: Focus on the Family, 8605 Explorer
Dr., Colorado Springs, CO  80920, 719/531-3400, fax 719/548-4525.
<BR>
