<DOCHDR>
http://www.sbsc.org:80/nationalreview/daily/nr112796.html 204.71.237.86 19970108091453 text/html 3156
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 09:15:09 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 02-Dec-96 23:55:41 GMT
Content-length: 2970
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>Washington Bulletin</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for November 27, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<I><B>TNR Watch</B></I><br>
Jeff Rosen's gargantuan cover story in the <I>New Republic</I> on "O.J. Simpson, critical race theory, American law, and the triumph of color over justice" is attracting a lot of attention. Hilton Kramer and Maureen Dowd have both called it "brilliant." We're fans of Rosen, but this time we must demur. The essay's critique of critical race theory is neither novel nor sufficiently pointed. The article's only original insight is the linkage between that theory and the Simpson trial, which is sort of obvious. Finally, his critique is more aesthetic than intellectual or moral. He uses the word "crude" more often than "wrong" to describe arguments. . . . 
<P>
In the same issue, Jacob Heilbrunnthe only person who has identified himself as one of the folks who joined Michael Lind's alleged exodus of intellectuals from the Righthas a shoddier article on "a startling new species: fellow travelers on the right" who apologize for anti-democratic regimes like Lee Kuan Yew's Singapore. Some of the examples are howlers: outgoing Sen. William Cohen ("R.," Me.) can hardly be described as part of the Right. A more glaring weakness is that Heilbrunn's proposed parallelism between the leftist attachment to Marxist regimes and revolutionaries and the right's alleged embrace of "Asian values" ignores the distinctioncentral to conservative foreign-policy thought for a decade and a halfbetween authoritarian and totalitarian regimes. Some conservatives may defend dictatorships on grounds that amount "to a relativistic multiculturalism." But a much older tradition of conservatism looks askance at the notion that there is one best set of political arrangements that works everywherenot because sound values vary from place to place, but because circumstances do. And lastly, Heilbrunn should have noted that plenty of conservatives have criticized Singapore's regime. Its censorship of reporter Christopher Lingle, an incident Heilbrunn mentions, was, for instance, the subject of a story in <I>National Review</I>.


<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
