<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for November 20, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<B>TNR Notes</B><br>

The latest <I>New Republic</I> includes an inaugural "TRB" column from its new editor, Michael Kelly, fresh from the <I>New Yorker</I>. It's as well written as ever, but more pointed and open in its political position: that of a chastened, centrist liberal. . . . We've had fun with Michael Walzer's effusions in the <I>New Republic</I>'s "The Hard Questions" column before. This week's isn't particularly amusing; it's just daft. Walzer argues that "the right way out of the 'culture wars'" is to provide government funding for groups like the Gay Men's Health Crisis and black Baptist nursery schools, in order to make these institutions as strong as groups like Catholic Charities and Lutheran Social Ministries, the expressions of an older "multiculturalism." Where to begin ticking off the conceptual problems here? Making independent organizations as government-dependent as Catholic Charities is a recipe not for a vibrant civil society but a neutered and standardized one. Moreover, diversity of "religion, ethnicity, race, and region" is not the same as multiculturalism and has never been so considered by its prominent latter-day critics. Catholics never demanded separatist group rights or their own language; Farrakhanites and Hispanic lobbies do. For them to demand state funds is to ask a polity to fund its own dissolution. And lastly, the phrase "culture wars" most importantly denotes conflicts over competing visions of justice, morality, human personhood, and their implications for such practices as abortion. Converting the Federal Government into a large Ford Foundation isn't going to make those conflicts disappear. 



<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
