<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for November 19, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<B>The Bi-Partisan Trap</B><br>
Newt Gingrich and Dick Gephardt held a joint press conference over the weekend that was full of talk of reconciliation, and completing the people's work, and bi-partisanship. Which is fine as far as it goes. There is no need for Republicans to be gratuitously partisan or confrontational with the Administration. But Republicans should also keep in mind that President Clinton built his political recovery on smart, well-managed partisan confrontation on the issues of his choosing: Medicare, the balanced budget, the government shut-downs. People hate partisan conflict in theory, but will endorse it in practice as long as it is marshaled against something they oppose (like the Clinton health-care bill back in 1993). Republicans might want to apply this lesson to the President's proposed intervention in Zaire. There is no national interest at stake, nor is it clear what goals U.S. troops would have in a mission there. Over the weekend the Administration had to re-consider the mission when Rwandan refugee began departing refugee camps in Zairewithout U.S. helpto head back to Rwanda; helping them make this trek was one of the goals of the U.S. intervention. The deeper problem in Zaire is that the government there is essentially non-existent, and if any intervention is going to have any long-term impact it will have to involve perilous and difficult "nation building." But that clearly is more than the American people will support; anything less thought is just a band aid. So why are American troops going to Zaire? And why aren't Republicans vocally opposing the idea? 


<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
